	     <tr><td id="headerrow" colspan="2" class="mform" valign="top"><a id="sj" href="/db/item.html?item=20366&amp;mid=106057910094632">RE: Really a bard weapon?</a> <a id="fs8" href="/db/item.html?item=20366&amp;mid=106057910094632#post"><img src="/shared/reply_to_thread_ico.gif" border="0" alt="Reply..." width="17" height="11" /></a>
	     <br clear="all" /><small>Posted @ Mon, Aug 11th 1:27 AM 2003</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign="top" id="fs8" class="mform"><span id="notbold">By:</span> <a href="/db/poster.html?user=226409"><span id=" ">kniedzw</span></a><br /><span id="notbold">11 posts<br /><span id="notbold">Score</span>: Decent [3.00]</td><td valign=top class="mform" width="100%"><p>The modifier on Marrow's Song is 2.0, compared with the epic's 1.8, so the modifier isn't quite the same.&nbsp;&nbsp;Moreover, the additional stats point more toward a bard (since high Cha reduces fizzles), but it's perfectly reasonable for a guild to reward this to another class, as the ratio is quite good.<br/><br/>SoE has lately pushed toward making items with instrument modifiers usable by more classes than just bards; look, for instance, at the Eye of Dreams, which has a 2.2 brass modifier but is ALL/ALL with stats that most people would find desirable.<br/><br/>I'm actually in favor of this, as it is a too-frequent occurance that I see class-specific loot rot because the classes in question present have the item (or better) already.  It's understandable that there would be some dissatisfaction with Sony's decisions, though.</p>&nbsp;<br /></td></tr>
